  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded reporting requirements\n\n3. Regulatory Enhancements\n- Increased customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technology Integration\n- Digital transaction monitoring systems\n- Advanced data analytics for detecting suspicious patterns\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n\n5. Global Compliance Standards\n- Expanding Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Risk-based assessment frameworks\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Blockchain and cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced beneficial ownership transparency\n- Stricter sanctions against financial crimes\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing prevention\n\nThe legislative approach has progressively become more comprehensive, technologically sophisticated, and internationally coordinated.",
